setwd("C:/Users/ebret/Desktop/Practicum")
df<-fread("weather_Data_reduced.csv",stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
#View(df)
#pull any valid baseball months
#weed out bad data results for pressure, these were obvious so I pulled them out
#sqldf('select max(pressure) from df')
head(df)
wd_filtered<-sqldf('select * from df where strftime("%m", Date) between "04" and "09" and pressure not in ("0","9985") ')
head(wd_filtered)
#Combining my day with date so that I get a primary key
wd_filtered<-sqldf('select distinct(Date) as Date,temp,pressure,humidity,wind_speed,wind_deg,clouds_all,Day_Night from wd_filtered')
wd1<-sqldf('select Day_Night||Date,temp,pressure,humidity,wind_speed ,wind_deg,clouds_all from wd_filtered')
#View(wd)
#head(wd1)

Histograms will help show the distribution of my data and highlight any overall trends. Such trends can include skewdness where the average and median differ to the extent that the histogram will be skewed left (median< mean) or skewed right (median<mean).

hist(wd1$temp,main="Temperature",xlab="Degrees F",ylab="Readings",breaks=15,col="#33006F")

hist(wd1$humidity,main="Humidity",xlab="% Humidity",ylab="Readings",breaks=15,col="#33006F")

hist(wd1$wind_speed,main="Wind Speed",xlab="Meters Per Sec",ylab="Readings",breaks=15,col="#33006F")

hist(wd1$wind_deg,main="Wind Degree",xlab="Degrees",ylab="Readings",breaks=15,col="#33006F")

hist(wd1$pressure,main="Pressure",xlab="Mbs",ylab="Readings",breaks=15,col="#33006F")

My results show that for my temperature and pressure measures the data is fairly normally distributed being skewed left. The opposite is true for wind speed and humidity which is skewed to the right. Wind degree has much less of a bell shaped curve, but this is also a bit different from the others as it uses a 360 degree scale to simulate the cardinal directions.

Boxplots will help to visually highlight a statistic summary of my data set. Additionally I will compare day and night atmospheric data across my measures.

boxplot(wd1$temp,main="Temperature",xlab="Degrees F",col="#33006F")

# set rownames and remove erronious day night as I am dividing the data into days vs night
wd <- wd1%>% select(-`Day_Night||Date`) 
#View(wd)
#Set all my measures to numeric so that they can be scaled
wd$pressure=as.numeric(wd$pressure)
wd$humidity=as.numeric(wd$humidity)
wd$wind_deg=as.numeric(wd$wind_deg)
wd$wind_speed=as.numeric(wd$wind_speed)
wd$clouds_all=as.numeric(wd$clouds_all)
wd <- as_tibble(wd)
#View(wd)
#str(wd)
#Scale my Data
wd_scaled <- scale(wd)
#Add back my row names
rownames(wd_scaled) <- wd1$`Day_Night||Date`
View(wd_scaled)

I will run clustering analysis for a large number of clusters than test the different outcomes using the elbow method and NbClust.

#Setting my seed so my results will be reproducable
set.seed=42
#in this step I create a way in which I will be able to run multiple numbers of clusters at the same time and the check them all togther. This makes things much more efficient for me.
kmean_calc <- function(df, ...){
  kmeans(df, scaled = ..., nstart = 25)
}
km2 <- kmean_calc(wd_scaled, 2)
km3 <- kmean_calc(wd_scaled, 3)

The Elbow method is used to determin the optimal number of clusters for my analysis. The Elbow Method is aproximate approach to detemrining the number of clusters, in general you want to pick a point of steep slope that turns into a shallow slope. In my example following cluster numbers of 3 and 4, I see a large drop then flattening of the slope.

#function to compute total within-cluster sum of squares
fviz_nbclust(wd_scaled, kmeans, method = "wss", k.max = 10, linecolor =   "#33006F") + theme_minimal() + ggtitle("The Elbow Method Both")

Since I was unable to conclusively select the number of clusters from my Elbow Test, I ran the nBClust which is a built in function that uses 30 indicies to determine the optimal number of clusters. The results are gathered by varying all combinations of number of clusters, distance measures as well as clustering methods.

res.nbclust <- NbClust(wd_scaled, distance = "euclidean",
                  min.nc = 2, max.nc = 9, 
                  method = "complete", index ="all")

## *** : The Hubert index is a graphical method of determining the number of clusters.
##                 In the plot of Hubert index, we seek a significant knee that corresponds to a 
##                 significant increase of the value of the measure i.e the significant peak in Hubert
##                 index second differences plot. 
## 

## *** : The D index is a graphical method of determining the number of clusters. 
##                 In the plot of D index, we seek a significant knee (the significant peak in Dindex
##                 second differences plot) that corresponds to a significant increase of the value of
##                 the measure. 
##  
## ******************************************************************* 
## * Among all indices:                                                
## * 3 proposed 2 as the best number of clusters 
## * 10 proposed 3 as the best number of clusters 
## * 4 proposed 4 as the best number of clusters 
## * 1 proposed 5 as the best number of clusters 
## * 3 proposed 6 as the best number of clusters 
## * 1 proposed 8 as the best number of clusters 
## * 1 proposed 9 as the best number of clusters 
## 
##                    ***** Conclusion *****                            
##  
## * According to the majority rule, the best number of clusters is  3 
##  
##  
## *******************************************************************
factoextra::fviz_nbclust(res.nbclust,barfill="#33006F") + theme_minimal()+  ggtitle("NbClust's optimal Num of clusters")
